# Pear Shaped Black Diamond Engagement Ring: The Complete {{year}} Guide (Settings, Sizes & Prices)

## TL;DR — Key Facts Before You Shop

- **The Opacity Advantage:** Black diamonds are fully opaque — they cannot transmit light, only reflect it from the surface. This eliminates bow-tie shadow, makes CO clarity grade universal and optically irrelevant, and means carat weight translates directly to face-up size with no brilliance variable. Every black pear diamond in this catalog is GIA or IGI Fancy Black-CO — and every one of them looks jet-black face-up regardless of the CO designation
- **The Carat-Per-Dollar Inversion:** In colorless diamonds, per-carat price rises with size. In black pear diamonds it falls: 1.17ct costs $1,368 ($1,169/ct); 4.70ct costs $5,255 ($1,118/ct); 7.45ct costs $6,715 ($901/ct). Maximum face-up black area at minimum cost per carat means buying as large as your budget allows — the opposite logic of colorless diamond buying
- **Cheapest entry:** [GIA 1.17ct Fancy Black-CO Pear](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/black-22037861?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at [$1,368](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/black-22037861?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — a full 1ct+ GIA-certified black pear for under $1,400
- **Best value large carat:** [GIA 4.70ct Fancy Black-CO Pear](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/black-22620299?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at [$5,255](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/black-22620299?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — lowest per-carat price in the 4ct+ tier at $1,118/ct
- **Most-reviewed setting for black:** [Twisted Halo in 14k White Gold](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/twisted-halo-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-item-sku-192890?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at [$1,955 (197 reviews)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/twisted-halo-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-item-sku-192890?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — white diamonds encircling a black pear center creates the highest contrast engagement ring available
- **Metal rule:** White gold for maximum drama (black-on-white); yellow gold for warm edgy contrast; rose gold for dark-romantic. Avoid platinum over white gold at a premium — black diamonds show no optical difference between the two
- **Contrarian Truth:** A 4.70ct GIA Fancy Black pear at $5,255 is more visually dominant than a 1ct GIA Fancy Black at $1,638 — and costs less per carat. The conventional colorless-diamond logic of "buy less stone to save money" is mathematically backwards for black diamonds. Buy the largest black pear your budget allows →

---

A pear shaped black diamond engagement ring is the most visually distinctive ring in the pear category: opaque, jet-black, and commanding in a way that no colorless or colored transparent diamond can replicate. The pear silhouette amplifies this — the elongated teardrop in black creates a bold, graphic shape that reads as architectural rather than decorative.

The buying logic for black pear diamonds is fundamentally different from any other diamond category. There are no cut grades to evaluate (black diamonds don't transmit light), no color modifiers to decode, no clarity tiers that matter visually, and no bow-tie to audit. Every stone in this catalog is GIA or IGI Fancy Black-CO. The entire purchase decision comes down to carat weight and setting.

This guide covers the complete Blue Nile black pear diamond catalog — 80+ stones from 1.01ct to 9.69ct — the two frameworks that govern every black pear purchase, and the specific pear settings that create maximum visual impact with a black center stone.

---

## The Opacity Advantage: Why Black Diamonds Require Different Buying Logic

The Opacity Advantage is the complete set of purchase simplifications that arise from a black diamond's opaque optical behavior — the properties that make buying a black pear easier and cheaper than buying a colorless pear of equivalent size.

**Why CO clarity grade is irrelevant for black diamonds.** CO is Blue Nile's Collection grade — below SI2, with inclusions visible to the naked eye in colorless diamonds. Every single black pear diamond in this catalog carries CO clarity, including the GIA and IGI certified stones. This is not a red flag — it is a structural property of black diamonds. Black diamonds are polycrystalline: they are formed from countless microscopic diamond crystals fused together, and the dark color comes precisely from the high density of inclusions, graphite, and structural irregularities within the stone. These "inclusions" are what create the black color. CO clarity on a black diamond has zero optical consequence — the stone is jet-black regardless.

**Why there is no bow-tie in a black pear.** Bow-tie shadow in a pear diamond occurs when light leaks through the center facets rather than reflecting back to the eye — a function of the stone's optical geometry under transparent light transmission. Black diamonds do not transmit light. There is no leakage to create a bow-tie pattern. The face-up appearance of a black pear is uniformly black at every angle, every lighting condition, every setting depth.

**Why all black pears are identically graded.** GIA's color grading for black diamonds has exactly one category: Fancy Black. There is no "Fancy Brownish Black," no "Fancy Grayish Black," no intensity modifiers. All certified black diamonds receive the same color grade. The only variables that differ between stones in this catalog are carat weight, exact physical dimensions, and price. This makes comparative shopping straightforward in a way that no other diamond category allows.

---

## The Carat-Per-Dollar Inversion: Buy Larger, Pay Less Per Carat

The Carat-Per-Dollar Inversion is the inverse price-per-carat relationship in black diamonds — where buying more carats costs less per carat, the structural opposite of colorless diamond pricing.

**The data in this catalog.** At the 1ct tier, per-carat prices range from $1,169/ct (1.17ct at $1,368) to $1,529/ct (1.03ct at $1,576). At the 2ct tier, per-carat prices fall to $1,350–$1,550/ct. At the 3ct tier: $1,200–$1,450/ct. At the 4–5ct tier: $1,100–$1,290/ct. At 7ct: $901–$1,260/ct. The per-carat cost of a black pear diamond decreases from roughly $1,500/ct at 1ct to $900/ct at 7ct.

**Why the inversion exists.** Black diamonds are valued almost entirely by weight — unlike colorless diamonds where cut precision, color purity, and clarity exclusivity create exponentially increasing premiums as size increases. Larger black diamond rough is not rare in the same way larger colorless rough is: black diamonds form in different geological conditions and in much higher supply. The market prices black diamonds primarily on weight, not on the compounding rarity of combined excellence in four independent grading axes.

**The practical buying implication.** A buyer with a $5,000 stone budget for a black pear should not purchase a 2ct stone at $2,900 when a 4.70ct stone at $5,255 costs less per carat and delivers more than twice the face-up surface area. In colorless diamonds, "buy less stone to save money" is often correct. In black pear diamonds, the same logic in reverse — "buy more stone to save money per carat" — is the correct application of the Inversion.

**The exception at 9ct+.** The per-carat price increases again at the 9ct+ tier (9.69ct at $13,005 = $1,342/ct). At very large sizes, supply tightens enough to reverse the Inversion. The optimal per-carat value tier for black pear diamonds is the 4ct–7ct range.

