The Carat-Per-Dollar Inversion is most visible here. The [GIA 4.70ct at $5,255](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/black-22620299?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) costs $1,118/ct — the lowest per-carat price in this entire catalog outside of the trophy tier. The [GIA 3.62ct at $5,193](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/black-27734833?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) costs more per carat ($1,434/ct) than the 4.70ct despite lower absolute price — this counterintuitive relationship is the Inversion at work.

For buyers in the $5,000–$7,000 stone budget, the correct decision is buying as large as possible within budget: the [GIA 5.14ct at $6,622](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/black-28008262?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) ($1,288/ct) delivers more per-carat value than the [GIA 3.26ct at $4,676](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/black-29304319?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) ($1,434/ct) and dramatically more face-up black area. For full pear size-to-visual-impact guidance, see the **[pear cut diamond buying guide](/pear-cut-diamond)**.

