## Care and Durability: What Black Pear Diamond Owners Need to Know

Black diamonds are polycrystalline — formed from microscopic diamond crystal aggregates rather than a single diamond crystal. This structure has practical implications for ring ownership that differ from colorless solitaire diamonds.

**Chip risk at the pear tip.** All pear diamonds carry chip risk at the pointed tip — the geometry concentrates stress at the terminal point. In black diamonds this risk is slightly elevated because the polycrystalline structure has more internal grain boundaries than single-crystal diamonds. A V-prong at the pear tip is mandatory, not optional. The vintage and halo settings in this guide — Twisted Halo, Interlaced Halo, Graduated Halo — all provide structured coverage at the tip that modern minimalist solitaires do not.

**Surface care.** Black diamonds are polished to a high mirror finish that shows fingerprints and oils more readily than colorless faceted stones because there is no internal brilliance to distract from surface contamination. Plan to clean a black pear ring every 1–2 weeks in warm soapy water with a soft brush. Avoid ultrasonic cleaners on black diamonds — the polycrystalline structure is more susceptible to vibration damage than single-crystal stones.

**Coating awareness.** Some black diamonds on the market are treated colorless or near-colorless diamonds with a black surface coating. All GIA and IGI certified "Fancy Black" diamonds in this catalog are naturally black — the GIA certificate specifically notes natural vs. treated color. Always verify GIA or IGI certification before purchasing any black diamond claimed as natural. Full pear durability and V-prong analysis in the **[pear shaped diamond ring guide](/pear-shaped-diamond-ring)**.

